Bringing an end to banditry and terrorism will benefit women and children because they are mostly at the receiving end of insecurity. This is the view expressed by participants during a virtual programme titled ‘Destiny moment with Eunice, fixing the woman’. It was hosted by a businesswoman and co-Pastor of the Winning Power Ministries International, Eunice Iferi-Chukwuemeka. Pastor Iferi-Chukwuemeka decried worsening insecurity in the country. “Many lives are lost daily. People can no longer go to farm. “Their economic power has been reduced to zero. Women have become widows and children, orphans.   Group to politicians: fear God     ‘I’ll ensure my constituents’ well-being’     PEBEC extends 7th National Action by 30 days   “We need to tackle these challenges we a faced with to avert crisis,” she said. Lamenting that women and children bear the burden of security crisis most times, a security expert, Pastor Ladi Thompson urged women to demand good governance. He said the government must adopt new strategies to tackle insecurity. “Also, there should be a deliberate effort by the government to allow women to participate actively in governance,” he said. Signals Brigade Commander, 6th Division Army, Port Harcourt, Rivers State, Brigadier General, Hassan Bawa, said the war against insecurity required collective effort. Another speaker, a retired police officer Mrs Hilda Ibufuro Harrison, advocated the re-orientation national values which must be passed to younger ones.